Practical Lab 3 - Univariate Linear Regression¶

Univariate Linear Regression on the California Housing Prices Dataset¶

🎯 Goal¶

This project aims to use simple linear regression models to understand how median house value is related to median income, population, and number of households. Analyzing each variable separately, we can determine which factor strongly correlates with median house value in the California district dataset. The result of this analysis will help to gain insights into the socioeconomic factors that impact housing prices in the area.

Source of Data: California Housing Prices

1. 📉 Median house value Vs. Median income¶

This linear regression model aims to understand how changes in household income influence housing prices. Through this model, we seek to establish a quantitative relationship between these two variables, enabling us to predict house values based on income levels.

In [ ]:
graph = sns.relplot(data=df_house[["median_house_value", "median_income"]], x="median_income", y="median_house_value", marker="P", aspect=2, height=6, color="darkblue")
plt.ylabel("Median house value")
plt.xlabel("Median income")
plt.title("Median house value Vs. Median income")

# plotting a resulting line on the existing scatter plot.

Conclusion and final insights¶

The models analyzed how different factors relate to house prices. The one focusing on income found a moderate link between higher incomes and higher house values. However, models examining households and population didn't show strong connections to house prices. Overall, while these models give some insights, they aren't perfect at predicting actual house values, suggesting they might need more factors to make better predictions.

✅ Collective house value prediction based on Income, Population and Households¶

In [ ]:
reg = linear_model.LinearRegression()
reg.fit(df_house[["median_income", "population", "households"]], df_house["median_house_value"])
X = df_test[["median_income", "population", "households"]]
X.reset_index(drop= True, inplace=True)
y_output = pd.DataFrame(reg.predict(df_test[["median_income", "population", "households"]]),columns=['Predicted House Value'])
y_output.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
df_predicted = pd.concat([X, y_output['Predicted House Value']],axis="columns")
df_predicted.head(10)

Geo-Housing: Latitude, Longitude, and Ocean Proximity Impact on Property Values¶

This model aims to understand how geographic and environmental factors influence housing prices. By incorporating latitude and longitude coordinates, we aim to capture spatial variations in property values, while 'ocean_proximity' is a proxy for environmental amenities or risks.

In [ ]:
df_filtered = df_house[['latitude', 'longitude', 'ocean_proximity']]
g = sns.relplot(data=df_filtered, x="latitude", y="longitude", hue="ocean_proximity" ,aspect=1.75, height=6)
